$CATEGORY: CIT/M5/week-14/14-7-agent-vs-simpler-flow-decision-matrix-direct-call-chained-ca

::q1:: In the four-tier decision matrix, which description best matches the "direct call" tier?
{
~The model is given a user question, retrieves matching documents from a vector database, and then generates an answer grounded in those documents. This pattern is used when the model was never trained on the data required to answer the question.#No — that description is RAG (Tier 3). A direct call does not involve any retrieval or vector database.
~The model runs through a planning loop, calls one or more external tools, reads the results, and then reasons about what to do next. This pattern is used when the number of steps cannot be fully scripted in advance.#No — that describes an agent (Tier 4). A direct call has no tools and no loop.
=A single prompt is sent to the model and a single response comes back, with no external tools, no retrieval, and no memory between calls. This is the cheapest and most predictable option, and it is the correct default when the answer already exists in the model's training data.#Correct — one prompt in, one response out, no moving parts. That is the direct call tier.
~Two or more model calls are linked in sequence, where the output of one call becomes the input of the next. This pattern is useful when a task has decomposable sub-steps that each benefit from a focused, isolated prompt.#No — linking multiple calls in sequence describes chained calls (Tier 2), not a direct call.
#### Tests whether learners can identify the direct call tier by its defining features (corpus §5.2).
}

::q2:: According to the decision matrix, what is the defining signal that a task belongs to the RAG tier rather than a simpler tier?
{
=The answer depends on data that the model was not trained on — such as private internal documents, information that changes frequently, or a source that must be cited precisely. A bare model answering from training data alone would hallucinate in these situations.#Correct — any of the three RAG signals (private data, freshness, or precision citation need) means the model lacks the required content and retrieval is necessary.
~The task has too many instructions to fit into a single prompt, so it must be split across two or more separate model calls, each receiving a portion of the work. This is detected when a single prompt produces noticeably lower-quality results than a broken-up version.#No — splitting work across multiple model calls describes chained calls (Tier 2). RAG is not triggered by prompt length but by whether the model was trained on the required data.
~The task requires the model to use multiple tools of different types — such as a search engine, a code runner, and a database query — and the number of tool calls varies depending on what the model finds at each step.#No — requiring multiple heterogeneous tools with dynamic step counts is the defining signal for the agent tier (Tier 4), not RAG.
~The answer is general knowledge that exists in the model's training data, but the user wants a longer, more structured response than a single prompt typically produces. Adding a retrieval step improves the formatting of the output.#No — if the answer is in training data and no external source is required, a direct call or chained calls is sufficient. RAG adds retrieval overhead that is only justified when training data is genuinely missing.
#### Tests the defining criterion for the RAG tier and distinguishes it from the other three tiers (corpus §5.4).
}

::q3:: A development team is building a customer support chatbot that must answer questions about their company's 500-page internal product manuals — PDFs the LLM has never been trained on. Which tier does the decision matrix point to, and why?
{
~Direct call (Tier 1), because the developer can paste the most important sections of the manuals into the system prompt and let the model answer from there. This avoids the complexity of a vector database entirely.#No — 500 pages of PDFs far exceed what can be pasted into a single prompt. More importantly, the core issue is that the model lacks the private content, which is the defining RAG signal.
~Chained calls (Tier 2), because the chatbot can break each user question into smaller sub-questions, ask the model each sub-question in sequence, and then combine the answers. No external retrieval is needed if the steps are structured carefully.#No — chained calls still rely entirely on the model's training data. Private internal documents the model was never trained on cannot be accessed through prompt chaining alone.
~Agent (Tier 4), because a 500-page document requires a loop that can decide which section to read next, call a file-reading tool, and accumulate information across multiple iterations before answering. A one-shot retrieval would miss important details spread across sections.#No — the task is retrieval followed by a single answer generation. It does not require multiple heterogeneous tools, real-time data, or dynamic step logic. An agent adds complexity without benefit here.
=RAG (Tier 3), because the answer depends on private internal documents that the model was never trained on. The documents must be embedded, stored in a vector database, and retrieved at query time so the model can ground its answer in actual product content.#Correct — the private-data signal is present. The model lacks the content, and RAG directly solves that by injecting retrieved document text into the prompt.
#### Tests application of the decision matrix to a scenario with a clear private-data signal (corpus §5.6, §5.7 Scenario C).
}

::q4:: Why does the decision matrix instruct engineers to start at the simplest tier and only move up when a specific criterion is met?
{
~Because simpler tiers produce more creative and varied responses than agents or RAG pipelines, making the outputs more suitable for tasks that require original writing or brainstorming. Complex systems tend to over-constrain the model and reduce output diversity.#No — creativity is not the reason. The rationale is about cost, reliability, and failure modes, not output variety.
=Because every tier above the simplest adds latency, cost per query, and additional failure points. An agent that does what a direct call could handle is slower, more expensive, and harder to debug — without delivering any extra value to the user.#Correct — complexity has real costs. The rule "use the simplest tier that works" prevents unnecessary latency, expense, and debugging burden.
~Because regulators and compliance frameworks typically prohibit agents from handling user-facing queries without a human in the loop, so engineers must exhaust simpler options before deploying any agentic system. This is a legal requirement in most jurisdictions.#No — the corpus does not state this as a compliance rule. The rationale is about engineering economics and reliability, not regulatory mandates.
~Because simpler tiers are easier for non-technical stakeholders to understand and audit, which builds user trust. If the system is not explainable to end users, it should not be deployed regardless of technical capability.#No — explainability is not the stated rationale in the decision matrix. The reason is that added complexity incurs real costs (latency, price, failure modes) without benefit when simpler tiers are sufficient.
#### Tests the engineering rationale behind the "start simple" default (corpus §5.1, §8).
}

::q5:: A developer asks a friend to review their new AI feature. The feature translates any user-submitted sentence into three other languages. The developer has built a full agent with a planning loop, tool calls to external translation APIs, and a ReAct reasoning step between each translation. What mistake does this represent?
{
~Under-engineering — the developer should have used RAG instead, because translation requires grounding in bilingual dictionaries and parallel corpora that the model was never trained on. Without retrieval, translation quality will be low.#No — translation of general sentences is well within the model's training data. The problem here is not missing data but unnecessary complexity, which is over-engineering.
~Under-engineering — the developer should have used chained calls instead of a direct call, because translating into three languages requires three separate prompts to maintain output quality for each language individually.#No — under-engineering means using too simple a system. This developer's system is too complex, not too simple. Chained calls might be acceptable for this task, but the flaw identified is over-engineering.
=Over-engineering — a direct call or at most chained calls is sufficient for translating sentences into three languages. The agent adds a planning loop and tool calls for a task that the model can handle entirely from training data, creating unnecessary latency and failure points.#Correct — the model already knows how to translate. There are no private documents, no dynamic tool requirements, and no unpredictable steps. An agent is wasteful here.
~Neither — an agent is always the safest choice because it can recover from errors that simpler tiers cannot handle. Using an agent for translation ensures the system gracefully retries if a translation looks incorrect.#No — agents are not universally safer. Each added loop and tool call is itself a new failure point. For a task the model handles reliably from training data, an agent introduces complexity without reducing risk.
#### Tests recognition of over-engineering — reaching for an agent when a direct call suffices (corpus §5.5, §8, §10).
}

::q6:: A team is building a research assistant that takes a user's question, searches the live web for recent academic papers, checks how many times each paper has been cited, summarises each abstract, and compiles a structured report — with the number of papers and tool calls varying depending on what the search returns. Which tier does the decision matrix point to?
{
=Agent (Tier 4), because the task requires multiple heterogeneous tools (web search, citation lookup, summarisation), uses real-time data, and has a dynamic number of steps that cannot be scripted in advance. The model must decide at runtime how many papers to examine and in what order.#Correct — all four agent signals are present: live data, multiple different tools, and a step count that varies by query. This is exactly the problem agents are designed to solve.
~RAG (Tier 3), because the task involves retrieving documents the model has never seen. The academic papers can be embedded into a vector database and retrieved on each query, which is sufficient to answer with current citations.#No — a static vector database cannot hold live web content. More importantly, the task requires combining a web search, a citation-count lookup, and a summarisation step in a dynamic order. That is multi-tool orchestration, not a one-shot retrieval.
~Chained calls (Tier 2), because the pipeline has clear sequential steps — search, then check citations, then summarise, then compile — and each step is just prompting the model with the output of the previous step. No special tools or loop logic is required.#No — chained calls rely on facts already in training data or the prompts. This task requires live web search and live citation data, which must come from external tools. The step count also varies per query, which chained calls cannot handle.
~Direct call (Tier 1), because a well-prompted model can search its training data for relevant papers on any topic, estimate citation counts from its knowledge, and produce a structured report in a single response. No external tools are needed for this kind of research summary.#No — the model's training data is not live. Recent papers, current citation counts, and real-time web content are not in the model's weights. A direct call would hallucinate specific citations and counts.
#### Tests application of the decision matrix to a scenario with all agent-tier signals present (corpus §5.5, §5.7 Scenario D).
}
